  "title": "Only partial column is used for composite index scan under mixed single-column and multi-column conditions",
  "description": "## Bug Report\n\nPlease answer these questions before submitting your issue. Thanks!\n\n### 1. Minimal reproduce step (Required)\n\n```\ncreate table t(a int, b int, c int, d int, index(a,b));\nexplain select * from t where  (a, b, c) in ((1, 1, 1), (2, 2, 2));\nexplain select * from t where  (a, b, c) in ((1, 1, 1), (2, 2, 2)) and d=1;\n```\n\n### 2. What did you expect to see? (Required)\n\nThe second query can use the two columns to build index range like the first query.\n\nRewrite as one multi-column condition:\n```\nmysql> explain select * from t where  (a, b, c, d) in ((1, 1, 1, 1), (2, 2, 2, 1));\n+-------------------------------+---------+-----------+------------------------+--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| id                            | estRows | task      | access object          | operator info                                                                                                                                                            |\n+-------------------------------+---------+-----------+------------------------+--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| IndexLookUp_11                | 0.16    | root      |                        |                                                                                                                                                                          |\n| ├─IndexRangeScan_8(Build)     | 0.20    | cop[tikv] | table:t, index:a(a, b) | range:[1 1,1 1], [2 2,2 2], keep order:false, stats:pseudo                                                                                                               |\n| └─Selection_10(Probe)         | 0.16    | cop[tikv] |                        | or(and(and(eq(test.t.a, 1), eq(test.t.b, 1)), and(eq(test.t.c, 1), eq(test.t.d, 1))), and(and(eq(test.t.a, 2), eq(test.t.b, 2)), and(eq(test.t.c, 2), eq(test.t.d, 1)))) |\n|   └─TableRowIDScan_9          | 0.20    | cop[tikv] | table:t                | keep order:false, stats:pseudo                                                                                                                                           |\n+-------------------------------+---------+-----------+------------------------+--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n4 rows in set (0.00 sec)\n```\n\n\n### 3. What did you see instead (Required)\n\n```\nmysql> explain select * from t where  (a, b, c) in ((1, 1, 1), (2, 2, 2)) and d=1;\n+-------------------------------+---------+-----------+------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| id                            | estRows | task      | access object          | operator info                                                                                                                                 |\n+-------------------------------+---------+-----------+------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| IndexLookUp_11                | 0.00    | root      |                        |                                                                                                                                               |\n| ├─IndexRangeScan_8(Build)     | 20.00   | cop[tikv] | table:t, index:a(a, b) | range:[1,1], [2,2], keep order:false, stats:pseudo                                                                                            |\n| └─Selection_10(Probe)         | 0.00    | cop[tikv] |                        | eq(test.t.d, 1), or(and(eq(test.t.a, 1), and(eq(test.t.b, 1), eq(test.t.c, 1))), and(eq(test.t.a, 2), and(eq(test.t.b, 2), eq(test.t.c, 2)))) |\n|   └─TableRowIDScan_9          | 20.00   | cop[tikv] | table:t                | keep order:false, stats:pseudo                                                                                                                |\n+-------------------------------+---------+-----------+------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n4 rows in set (0.00 sec)\n```\n\n### 4. What is your TiDB version? (Required)\n\nv7.1.2\n\n",
